> Roasting cauliflower in thick slices transforms it into a hearty main dish! Tzatziki - everyone's favorite Greek condiment - is a tangy, protein-packed topping for these steaks. Serves on a bed of whole grain bulgur, it's both healthy and filling.

== Roasted Cauliflower Steaks ==

Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Cut the @cauliflower{1} lengthwise into 1-inch thick
steaks. Toss the cauliflower steaks with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp} on a
#baking sheet{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Place in the oven for
~{25-30%minutes}, until tender and browned.

== Bulgur ==

Bring @water{1%cup}, the @veggie stock concentrate{1} and a pinch of @salt{}
to a boil in a #small pot{}. Add the @bulgur wheat{1/2%cup}, cover, and reduce
to a simmer for ~{12-15%minutes}, until tender.

== Spiced Oil ==

Meanwhile, heat @olive oil{2%tbsp} in a #small pan{} over medium heat. Stir in
the @chili flakes{1%tsp} (to taste, start with ¼ teaspoon, you can always add more
if you want it spicier), @cumin{1%tsp}, and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.
Cook for ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant, then set aside.

== Tzatziki Yogurt Sauce ==

Peel and dice the @cucumber{1}(peeled and diced). Chop the @dill{1/4%ounce}(chopped)
and halve @lemon{1}. In a #small bowl{}, combine @yogurt{5.3%ounce}, 1/4 cup diced
cucumber, half the dill, and a squeeze of lemon. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

== Assembly ==

Plate the bulgur and top with the roasted cauliflower steaks, tzatziki yogurt
sauce, remaining cucumber, @pepitas{1%ounce}, and a drizzle of spiced oil. Garnish
with the remaining dill and enjoy!